<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">03 — Technology</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">What Makes AGA Different to Service</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">The Classic AGA's heat storage philosophy is fundamentally different from any other cooking appliance. Understanding this changes everything about how service is approached.</p>

    <div class="features-2col">
      <ul class="features-list">
        <li><strong>Heat Storage vs Conventional Cooking</strong> — Classic AGA maintains massive cast iron ovens at fixed temperatures using a continuous low-output heat source. The "roasting oven" is always approximately 400–450°F; the "simmering oven" always 250–300°F. There's no thermostat in the oven — the oven temperature is determined by the heat source output and the thermal mass of the cast iron. Diagnosis starts at the heat source, not the oven.</li>
        <li><strong>Always-On Operation</strong> — A Classic AGA is never turned off in normal use. The heat source runs 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. This means thermostat and gas valve components are in continuous operation — wear occurs from extended hours of use, not from on/off cycling. Annual service is strongly recommended to assess gas valve and thermostat condition before complete failure.</li>
        <li><strong>Cast Iron Thermal Mass</strong> — The ovens' cast iron mass is the cooking medium — heat radiates from the iron surfaces rather than from a heating element or gas flame inside the oven. This produces specific cooking characteristics (exceptional roasting, slow braises) but also means temperature recovery after a cooking session is slow. When an AGA is "not recovering" between uses, the heat source thermostat or gas valve is typically the cause.</li>
        <li><strong>Fixed Oven Temperatures</strong> — Classic AGA ovens are not adjustable — the roasting oven is always roasting temperature, the simmering oven is always simmering temperature. Cooking technique adapts to the range; the range does not adapt to the cook's temperature preference. This is why temperature calibration on a Classic AGA means calibrating the heat source, not adjusting an oven control.</li>
        <li><strong>Radiant Heat Distribution</strong> — Classic AGA ovens cook by radiation from all cast iron surfaces simultaneously — top, bottom, and sides. This is why AGA cooking produces characteristic results: evenly browned roasts, consistent baked goods. When results become uneven, the heat source is losing output evenly enough to drop below the threshold where consistent radiation occurs across all surfaces.</li>
        <li><strong>AGA Total Control vs Classic Diagnostic Split</strong> — Total Control units have individual electric elements in each oven and can be independently controlled. When a Total Control oven stops heating, the diagnosis follows conventional oven diagnostic logic: element test, temperature sensor test, control board assessment. This is completely different from Classic diagnosis. We confirm which AGA model we're working on before any diagnostic approach.</li>
      </ul>
      <div>
        <div class="tip-block" style="background:#0a0f1a; border-color:#2a5ea5; margin-top:0">
          <div class="tip-label" style="color:#6aabff">🏡 AGA in LA — Where These Ranges Live</div>
          <div class="tip-text" style="color:#bbb">AGA's LA market is concentrated in homes with strong English character: English Tudor estates in Hancock Park and Fremont Place where an AGA is the natural kitchen centerpiece, Pasadena and San Marino Craftsman homes where the AGA's warmth and permanence suits the architecture, and Malibu and Pacific Palisades properties where the always-on warmth is valued year-round. AGA owners in LA are almost always long-committed devotees — people who understand and embrace the heat storage philosophy, who have adapted their cooking to the range rather than the reverse. When their AGA needs service, they want a technician who respects what they have.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tip-block" style="background:#100a0a; border-color:#c8820a; margin-top:16px">
          <div class="tip-label" style="color:#e8a030">⏱️ Classic AGA Preheat — Not What New Owners Expect</div>
          <div class="tip-text" style="color:#bbb">One of the most common AGA-related service calls we receive is from new owners who think their Classic AGA is broken because the ovens "aren't hot enough." We always ask: how long has the AGA been running since last service, or since installation? A Classic AGA takes 75 minutes to 8 hours to fully saturate with heat depending on the model and configuration — the AGA Dual Control takes approximately 8 hours from cold to reach full operating temperature. This isn't a malfunction. It's the heat storage system working as designed. We confirm heat saturation time before any diagnosis on recently installed or recently serviced Classic AGA units.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">04 — Common Problems</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Most Common AGA Failures in Los Angeles</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🔥 Classic AGA Running Cool</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Gas thermostat drift or gas valve restriction — the heat source isn't maintaining the output needed to keep the cast iron at operating temperature. We test gas valve output, thermostat calibration, and burner assembly on every Classic AGA temperature call. Thermostat drift is the most common cause — the always-on thermostat wears from continuous operation over years of use.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-classic">Classic AGA</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🚪 Cast Iron Door Not Sealing</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Door hinge wear from the cumulative weight of the cast iron door. The hinge gradually allows the door to sag, preventing flush seating on the oven seal. Lost door seal means lost radiant heat — the oven temperature drops. We check door alignment and hinge tension on every Classic AGA temperature call alongside the heat source, because both can be contributing causes.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-common">Most Common</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">⚡ Total Control Oven Not Heating</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Individual electric heating element failure in the affected oven cavity. Each Total Control oven has its own element — when one oven doesn't heat while others do, the fault is in that oven's element or its individual control circuit. We test elements and control boards independently for each oven cavity. Control board failure affecting all ovens simultaneously is also possible.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-tc">Total Control</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">✨ Enamel Chipping</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Physical impact at corners and edges — usually from cookware contact or cleaning tool impact. AGA's high-heat formulated enamel is durable but not impact-proof. Chips cannot be repaired in-situ. We document location and size and advise on AGA Customer Care's professional respray service when chipping is significant. For minor chips, AGA's touch-up enamel pen provides aesthetic improvement without full respray.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-enamel">Enamel Finish</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🌀 Pilot Light / Ignition Failure</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Gas Classic AGA pilot light or electronic ignition failure — the pilot that maintains the main burner. When the pilot fails, the main burner cannot light and the AGA goes cold over several hours as the cast iron radiates its stored heat. Emergency service for Classic AGA pilot failure — cold cast iron AGA means no cooking capability and hours to recover even after repair.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-classic">Classic AGA</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🔁 Slow Heat Recovery</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Gas valve or thermostat operating at below-spec output — the heat source is functional but not producing enough output to replenish heat quickly after heavy cooking sessions. The oven eventually recovers but takes much longer than the model's specification. Same-day cooking of multiple courses becomes difficult. Thermostat calibration or gas valve cleaning often resolves this without full replacement.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-classic">Classic AGA</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

