<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">09 — FAQ</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">AGA Repair FAQ</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">My Classic AGA isn't as hot as it used to be — what's wrong?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">For gas Classic AGA: the gas thermostat has drifted from calibration or the gas valve is restricting output. The cast iron ovens themselves don't fail — they're passive. We diagnose the heat source (thermostat and gas valve) first. Thermostat calibration resolves many Classic AGA temperature complaints without any parts replacement. Also check: door seal and hinge alignment — a poorly sealing door causes heat loss from the oven cavity.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What's the difference between Classic AGA, Total Control, and Mercury?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Classic AGA: always-on heat storage using gas or oil — never turned off, ovens maintained at fixed temperatures permanently. AGA Total Control: electric model that can be turned on and off, individual oven elements controlled independently. Mercury/Elise: conventional cooking ranges in AGA styling — not heat storage. Each requires a completely different service approach. We confirm the model before any diagnosis.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does it take for a Classic AGA to heat up after repair?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">From cold: 75 minutes for standard gas Classic models, up to 8 hours for AGA Dual Control from completely cold. After routine service where the AGA was only briefly cooled: typically 1–2 hours to full operating temperature. We always give owners a specific recovery time estimate after Classic AGA service — it's one of the most important things to communicate so the repair isn't mistaken for incomplete.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Where is the AGA made?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Classic AGA cast iron range cookers are manufactured in Coalbrookdale, Shropshire, England — the heart of the British Industrial Revolution, where the AGA was invented by Dr. Gustaf Dalén in 1922. Classic AGA manufacturing remains in Coalbrookdale today. AGA's modern Mercury and Elise ranges may be manufactured at other facilities.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can AGA enamel be repaired if it chips?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Minor chips can be addressed with AGA's touch-up enamel pen for aesthetic improvement. Significant chipping requires professional respray through AGA Customer Care (1-800-241-9152) — the enamel must be matched to the specific color and fired at temperature, which cannot be done in-situ. We document all chip locations during service and can provide the referral to AGA Customer Care for respray assessment.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How often should a Classic AGA be serviced?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Annual service is recommended for Classic AGA. The always-on operation means thermostat and gas valve components accumulate significant hours — a Classic AGA gas thermostat runs 8,760 hours per year versus a conventional range thermostat that might run 200-500 hours. Annual service catches thermostat drift, burner condition, door hinge wear, and door seal compression loss before they become failures.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
